[{"id":30546,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Hydrocarbons","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></math>&nbsp;only","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></math>&nbsp;only","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi></math>&nbsp;only","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></math>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></math>"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>In basic or neutral medium <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi><mo>-</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi></math> coupling favourable while in slightly acidic medium <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>CN</mi></math> coupling favourable.</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/232797a8-db5d-4593-9dd3-f8b49cca2263-image.png\" style=\"width: 444px; height: 742px;\" /></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (25 Feb Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":30562,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Hydrocarbons","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/1390ca8a-8752-438a-bc22-693cd9e1d5ee-image.png\" style=\"width: 163px; height: 78px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/dbe5d9b1-e71a-43f5-8c1e-bd9e3d02ca41-image.png\" style=\"width: 174px; height: 83px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/0f934a48-b40d-4922-9dc5-f661ac7c44f3-image.png\" style=\"width: 146px; height: 100px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/8cf2c753-3f69-4d7e-b067-b85f3b126fb6-image.png\" style=\"width: 107px; height: 98px;\" />"],"answer":3,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/377e0598-9ac0-4b57-a024-8359bc8f8125-image.png\" style=\"width: 456px; height: 161px;\" />&nbsp;","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2020 (03 Sep Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":30574,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Hydrocarbons","question":"","options":["<math><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi></mrow></mfenced><mo>,</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\"></mi><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">c</mi></mrow></mfenced></math> and <math><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi></mrow></mfenced></math>","<math><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi></mrow></mfenced></math> only","<math><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">c</mi></mrow></mfenced></math> only","<math><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">b</mi></mrow></mfenced></math> and <math><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi></mrow></mfenced></math>"],"answer":2,"solution":"<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/baf8d7b4-5ba9-4d2a-9dce-e7c347420db2-719.png\" style=\"height: 471px; width: 464px;\" /></p><p>We have to know that a Saytzeff product is basically an alkene compound which has undergone many substitution reactions to form the alkene product. From Saytzeff rule, a stable alkene is formed when removal of hydrogen from beta carbon has a low number of hydrogen atoms.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2020 (07 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":30596,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Hydrocarbons","question":"","options":["<p><img height=\"95\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/386d892f-f49e-431c-87a2-1a7cfd3eddd7-image.png\" width=\"107\" /></p>","<p><img height=\"67\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/14c6816d-8720-4e0d-882e-677723d58a7a-image.png\" width=\"189\" /></p>","<p><img height=\"100\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/f069343e-c266-4026-b7c8-794a704a971b-image.png\" width=\"150\" /></p>","<p><img height=\"95\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/48af9c3f-ea2f-4146-bc84-587fbf3c034b-image.png\" width=\"130\" /></p>"],"answer":1,"solution":"<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/7b84c563-766f-4c6e-bf5d-79d7084b94a0-2741b4ad-f9ef-4136-a20b-ee22c52e91c8-image.png\" style=\"width: 628px; height: 214px;\" /></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2018 (16 Apr Online)","image":null},{"id":30544,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Hydrocarbons","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mi>COCl</mi><mo>/</mo><msub><mi>AlCl</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>,</mo><msub><mi>Br</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>/</mo><msub><mi>AlBr</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>,</mo><msub><mi>HNO</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>/</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi>SO</mi><mn>4</mn></msub><mo>,</mo><mi>Zn</mi><mo>/</mo><mi>HCl</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mi>COCl</mi><mo>/</mo><msub><mi>AlCl</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>,</mo><mi>Zn</mi><mo>-</mo><mi>Hg</mi><mo>/</mo><mi>HCl</mi><mo>,</mo><msub><mi>Br</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>/</mo><msub><mi>AlBr</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>,</mo><msub><mi>HNO</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>/</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi>SO</mi><mn>4</mn></msub></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>HNO</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>/</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi>SO</mi><mn>4</mn></msub><mo>,</mo><msub><mi>Br</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>/</mo><msub><mi>AlCl</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>,</mo><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mi>COCl</mi><mo>/</mo><msub><mi>AlCl</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>,</mo><mi>Zn</mi><mo>-</mo><mi>Hg</mi><mo>/</mo><mi>HCl</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>Br</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>/</mo><msub><mi>AlBr</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>,</mo><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mi>COCl</mi><mo>/</mo><msub><mi>AlCl</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>,</mo><msub><mi>HNO</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>/</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi>SO</mi><mn>4</mn></msub><mo>,</mo><mi>Zn</mi><mo>/</mo><mi>HCl</mi></math>"],"answer":1,"solution":"<p>Benzene is an aromatic compound which shows the characteristic reaction of electrophilic aromatic substitution reactions. This is because the reaction is initiated by an electrophile.</p><p>Benzene reacts with&nbsp;CH<sub>3</sub>â€‹Cl&nbsp;in presence of anhydrous&nbsp;AlCl<sub>3</sub>â€‹&nbsp;to give Toulene. This is fridel crafts Alkylation and an electrophillic substitution.</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/a1cbb360-b07a-4b6a-b656-1f002da56617-image.png\" style=\"width: 298px; height: 350px;\" /></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (25 Feb Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":30577,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Hydrocarbons","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/55de67e1-02d0-49d0-aa64-0030c5fb71c2-image.png\" style=\"width: 160px; height: 113px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/9180d02a-aa0b-493f-8b43-f3ea35981546-image.png\" style=\"width: 180px; height: 76px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/b1ab2e50-3762-488f-93e3-accb3f4e82d8-image.png\" style=\"width: 160px; height: 82px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/93928ad0-be72-4ceb-9af4-742310e61d9e-image.png\" style=\"width: 160px; height: 72px;\" />"],"answer":1,"solution":"<p>This reaction is the halohydration of alkene. It is an electrophilic addition reaction.</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/61fb1145-f910-4446-bb82-e55aa173bf07-ef335eea-7a20-41d2-ac30-736362ebb571-image.png\" style=\"width: 500px; height: 62px;\" /><br /><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/b9383e0f-b370-4281-b699-b62221f1f947-image48.png\" style=\"width: 500px; height: 227px;\" /></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2019 (12 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":30458,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Hydrocarbons","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/10c99310-0d35-44a0-a79d-8f433631195b.png\" style=\"width: 150px; height: 197px;\"/>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/e83ff9f3-dd71-4404-a88b-1dd71d59f0b3.png\" style=\"width: 150px; height: 191px;\"/>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/5cc9dc4c-38c3-4dec-9be8-b51c4d8a1fd6.png\" style=\"width: 150px; height: 212px;\"/>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/6df60ca3-0fd8-4af9-a21d-a896c7ee5868.png\" style=\"width: 170px; height: 233px;\"/>"],"answer":2,"solution":"<p>During an electrophilic addition reactions double bonds donate lone pair electrons to an electrophile.</p><p>Markovnikov's Rule: The addition of a proton <span style=\"background-color:null;\">acid</span> to the double bond of an alkene results in a product with the acid hydrogen bound to the carbon atom that already has the greater number of hydrogen attached.</p><p>In the given reaction electrophile <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi><mo>+</mo></msup></math> adds to the double bond, a carbocation is formed. Then <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi>Cl</mi><mo>-</mo></msup></math> is added at the electron deficient carbocation.</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/88865b3e-9c8b-4648-bcc8-41fc49554fe5.png\" style=\"width: 767px; height: 207px;\"/></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (31 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":30471,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Hydrocarbons","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>The hydrogen bromide addition in peroxides follows Anti Markovnikov rule.  Anti Markovnikov  addition reaction is found to follow a free radical mechanism. The peroxide compound involved helps in the generation of free radicals. The Anti-Markovnikov rule defines regiochemistry in which the substituent is attached to a less substituted carbon instead of the more substituted carbon.</p><p>The reaction of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>3</mn><mo>-</mo></math>Methylhex-2-ene  with <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>HBr</mi></math> in presence of peroxide, takes place as follows,</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/af7b767c-8d53-40bf-9f4c-761a0924ba2f.png\" style=\"width: 400px; height: 200px;\"/></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn></math> chiral carbons, here, so, total number of stereoisomers will be <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mn>2</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi></msup><mo>=</mo><msup><mn>2</mn><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>=</mo><mn>4</mn></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (27 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":30398,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Hydrocarbons","question":"","options":["","","",""],"answer":3,"solution":"The structure of \"S\" is 2-methylcyclopent-1-ene-1-carboxylic acid.<br><br>Since \"S\" is obtained by the acidification of the product from the iodoform reaction of \"R\", \"R\" must contain a methyl ketone group ($-COCH_3$). The iodoform reaction converts the $-COCH_3$ group into a $-COOH$ group alongside the formation of a yellow precipitate of iodoform ($CHI_3$). Therefore, the structure of \"R\" is 1-acetyl-2-methylcyclopentene.<br><br>\"R\" is formed by the intramolecular aldol condensation of \"Q\". Performing a retro-aldol condensation on \"R\" by cleaving the double bond in the cyclopentene ring yields octane-2,7-dione as \"Q\" ($CH_3-CO-CH_2-CH_2-CH_2-CH_2-CO-CH_3$).<br><br>\"Q\" is obtained by the ozonolysis of \"P\". To determine the structure of \"P\", we perform retro-ozonolysis by removing the oxygen atoms from the two carbonyl groups of \"Q\" and connecting the corresponding carbon atoms with a double bond. Connecting the C2 and C7 carbons forms a six-membered ring with methyl groups at the double bond.<br><br>Thus, \"P\" is 1,2-dimethylcyclohexene.<br><br>Answer:","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2026 (05 April Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":30557,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Hydrocarbons","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/28ed8306-c58b-4f58-8c94-60d705123b33-image.png\" style=\"width: 146px; height: 210px;\" />&nbsp;&nbsp;","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/47d4dbad-aa99-44f5-9ac5-5f4e776bb691-image.png\" style=\"width: 146px; height: 200px;\" />&nbsp;&nbsp;","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/addd3787-737a-4f90-b37c-3d811fded215-image.png\" style=\"width: 176px; height: 200px;\" />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/16a99e4b-8d32-44e8-a89e-062db3331d2b-image.png\" style=\"width: 153px; height: 200px;\" />&nbsp;&nbsp;"],"answer":3,"solution":"<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/81002fbd-d7c8-46f2-8df6-971c9e8fc79b-image.png\" style=\"width: 406px; height: 400px;\" />&nbsp;&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2020 (06 Sep Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":30495,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Hydrocarbons","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<blockquote><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/7279e8a6-4be2-4a38-a131-169dea3231d8-fb96104f-2652-47a4-b717-82139edfb1c9-image.png\" style=\"width: 364px; height: 120px;\" /></p><p>According to the above chemical reaction, 2 moles of bromine will give one mole of the product.</p><p>2 moles of&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>Br</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>=</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>160</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">g</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>of</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><msub><mi>Br</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>gives</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>one</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>mole</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>of</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>product</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>=</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>360</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">g</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>of</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>product</mi></math></p><p>So, mass of product formed from&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>gm</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>of</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><msub><mi>Br</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>will</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>be</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>360</mn><mrow><mn>2</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>160</mn></mrow></mfrac><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>1</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">g</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>=</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mfrac><mn>9</mn><mn>8</mn></mfrac><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">g</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>of</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>product</mi></math></p><p>But given that % yield = 27%.</p><p>So actual amount of product&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mfrac><mn>9</mn><mn>8</mn></mfrac><mo>&#215;</mo><mfrac><mn>27</mn><mn>100</mn></mfrac><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>=</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>30</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>g</mi><mi>r</mi><mi>a</mi><mi>m</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>3</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">g</mi></math></p></blockquote>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (29 Jul Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":30598,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Hydrocarbons","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/DeJskMhDX5M8JS4brKF44wf8U3TyPG1gOZKAJ1dqFaU.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/PZ9hvlJzoeI1PXyYdVehhtnZPVr2wgw2KO851jQLkkw.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/dY7g4Eto_UrAfelUSmDdjfFkyu0XZWv6Kl9-kCekbG4.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/ABMxMxBM9s74TwjYqf66hFLkQ5r_27NxRI43tyNGoWU.original.fullsize.png\"><br>"],"answer":0,"solution":"Note: In the given reaction a molecule of $\\mathrm{HCl}$ is lost and $\\mathrm{C}=\\mathrm{C}$ double bond is formed. Thus it is dehydrohalogenation reaction.\nNitro group is electron withdrawing group. Hence increases the acidity of $\\mathrm{H}$ atom (attached to $\\mathrm{C}$ atom bearing nitro group) which is removed easily. Further the newly formed double bond is in conjugation with nitro group.\n<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/0Y-pUsuIdxQlmtM75eNgOgkqe1WY1Rkw5n_LlQt8Bpk.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2018 (15 Apr Shift 2 Online)","image":null},{"id":30400,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Hydrocarbons","question":"","options":["$90$","$118$","$160$","$125$"],"answer":1,"solution":"Addition of $Br_2$ to styrene (X) yields 1,2-dibromoethylbenzene.<br><br>$C_6H_5-CH=CH_2 \\xrightarrow{Br_2/CHCl_3} C_6H_5-CH(Br)-CH_2(Br)$<br><br>Reaction with excess $NaNH_2$ causes double dehydrohalogenation followed by deprotonation of the terminal alkyne, forming sodium phenylacetylide.<br><br>$C_6H_5-CH(Br)-CH_2(Br) \\xrightarrow{NaNH_2 \\text{ (excess)}} C_6H_5-C \\equiv C^- Na^+$<br><br>Nucleophilic substitution with $CH_3I$ yields 1-phenylpropyne.<br><br>$C_6H_5-C \\equiv C^- Na^+ \\xrightarrow{CH_3I} C_6H_5-C \\equiv C-CH_3$<br><br>Reduction with $Na/NH_3(l)$ reduces the internal alkyne to a trans-alkene without affecting the benzene ring.<br><br>$C_6H_5-C \\equiv C-CH_3 \\xrightarrow{Na/NH_3(l)} C_6H_5-CH=CH-CH_3$<br><br>The major product (Y) is trans-1-phenylpropene, which has the molecular formula $C_9H_{10}$.<br><br>Molar mass of $C_9H_{10} = (9 \\times 12) + (10 \\times 1) = 108 + 10 = 118 \\text{ g mol}^{-1}$.<br><br>Answer: $118$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2026 (04 April Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":30464,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Hydrocarbons","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mo>-</mo><msub><mi>CrO</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>  </mo><mo> </mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mo>-</mo><msub><mi>CrO</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>A</mi><mo>-</mo><mo> </mo><msub><mi>CrO</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>  </mo><mo> </mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mo>-</mo><msub><mi>CrO</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi>Cl</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mo>-</mo><msub><mi>CrO</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi>Cl</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>  </mo><mo> </mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mo>-</mo><msub><mi>CrO</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi>Cl</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mo>-</mo><msub><mi>CrO</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi>Cl</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>  </mo><mo> </mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mo>-</mo><msub><mi>CrO</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math>"],"answer":1,"solution":"<p>Toluene or substituted toluene is converted to benzylidene diacetate on treating with chromic oxide in acetic anhydride. The benzylidene diacetate can be hydrolysed to corresponding benzaldehyde with aqueous acid.</p><p>Chromyl chloride oxidises<br/>methyl group to a chromium complex, which on hydrolysis<br/>gives corresponding benzaldehyde. The reaction is known as Etard reaction.</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/2e946792-c97f-4635-9248-950de9c558f3.png\" style=\"width: 600px; height: 271px;\"/></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (30 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":30566,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Hydrocarbons","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/45aa295f-cb49-4a18-8fb2-a9ee2dfbd583-image.png\" style=\"width: 144px; height: 76px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/c012048c-fdb8-4e6c-bf96-c8f57e28da6f-image.png\" style=\"width: 118px; height: 94px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/b0662f0e-a260-4d27-aa61-85c7fd848c96-image.png\" style=\"width: 115px; height: 109px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/4c1389e8-f756-4db2-a69c-aa5ff07f29ac-image.png\" style=\"width: 133px; height: 120px;\" />"],"answer":1,"solution":"&nbsp;","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2020 (02 Sep Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":30616,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Hydrocarbons","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/gThXEaNogFuIoOaRO5q27DvaPrGlwo6LW9NF7U3E0Vc.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/EojC9Lr8jkzWyq-smlE7kB7WE9fNaNpRLt-qmxOTYTc.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/x7ZY35KI48s6cnXp2_re4rxYkUAT2xwdYruzAzCKxIQ.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/_6BCuKM51sL2ohKpDp7j3U9wQeFXk6x_XBGA-iyJEWo.original.fullsize.png\"><br>"],"answer":2,"solution":"The major component of Borsch reagent is 2,4- dinitrophenyl hydrazine which can be obtained by reaction of 2,4-dinitrochloro benzene and hydrazine\n<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/RRG8qBuKpt1U3eB-Jwk7N1jUCKZByAfjwEe-TXAtbBI.original.fullsize.png\"><br><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/n-lxFT54f0PvQPDekDXp5G7QkLPI-8jeto7HfnBIb_c.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2013 (22 Apr Online)","image":null},{"id":30472,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Hydrocarbons","question":"","options":["<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/c0f53cea-c788-4964-97d5-5b978306d962.png\" style=\"width: 278px; height: 91px;\" /></p>","<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/c8c1e3e5-525d-4d18-ac6f-9b8b4b3c78d9.png\" style=\"width: 191px; height: 153px;\" /></p>","<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/3852a4b6-7534-4fa9-9328-97ad5377bc49.png\" style=\"width: 255px; height: 88px;\" /></p>","<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/8ed707b0-b3cd-4c5f-9ac5-a8f176284918.png\" style=\"width: 301px; height: 43px;\" /></p>"],"answer":2,"solution":"<p>Hydroboration-oxidation of terminal alkenes give primary alcohols. Propene gives propanol. Propanol on oxidation with PCC gives propanal. Propanal undergo nucleophilic addition reaction with methyl magnesium bromide give 2-butanol.</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/5338f041-4948-41d1-a392-779a0c6acf91.png\" style=\"width: 454px; height: 276px;\" /></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (15 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":30525,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Hydrocarbons","question":"","options":["The reaction is not possible in acidic medium","Both compounds A&nbsp;and B&nbsp;are formed equally","Compound A will be the major product","Compound B&nbsp;will be the major product"],"answer":2,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/3ad212d3-2ec9-4a1c-a52f-c5ae3557a8b8-image.png\" style=\"width: 334px; height: 306px;\" />","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (27 Jul Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":30402,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Hydrocarbons","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"Step 1: The first reaction is a Friedel-Crafts alkylation. Benzene reacts with $CH_3Cl$ in the presence of anhydrous $AlCl_3$ to form toluene.<br><br>Step 2: The second reaction is electrophilic aromatic substitution. Toluene reacts with $Cl_2$ in the presence of $FeCl_3$ to form a mixture of o-chlorotoluene and p-chlorotoluene. Due to steric hindrance at the ortho position, the major product is p-chlorotoluene.<br><br>Step 3: The third reaction is the oxidation of the alkyl side chain. p-chlorotoluene is oxidized by $K_2Cr_2O_7 / H_2SO_4$ to form p-chlorobenzoic acid, which is the major product $(X)$.<br><br>The molecular formula of p-chlorobenzoic acid is $C_7H_5ClO_2$.<br>Molar mass of $(X) = (7 \\times 12) + (5 \\times 1) + 35.5 + (2 \\times 16) = 84 + 5 + 35.5 + 32 = 156.5 \\text{ g mol}^{-1}$.<br><br>Step 4: Reaction of p-chlorobenzoic acid with $NaHCO_3$ liberates $CO_2$ gas:<br>$C_6H_4ClCOOH + NaHCO_3 \\rightarrow C_6H_4ClCOONa + H_2O + CO_2 \\uparrow$<br><br>From the stoichiometry, $1$ mole of p-chlorobenzoic acid produces $1$ mole of $CO_2$ gas.<br>Volume of $CO_2$ liberated at STP = $11.2 \\text{ dm}^3$.<br>Moles of $CO_2$ liberated = $\\dfrac{11.2}{22.4} = 0.5 \\text{ mol}$.<br><br>Therefore, moles of p-chlorobenzoic acid reacted = $0.5 \\text{ mol}$.<br>Mass of $(X)$ reacted, $P = 0.5 \\text{ mol} \\times 156.5 \\text{ g mol}^{-1} = 78.25 \\text{ g}$.<br><br>Answer: $78.25$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2026 (04 April Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":30500,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Hydrocarbons","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>6</mn></msub></math> and&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>Cl</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mover><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>&#729;</mo></mover><msub><mi>HCl</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math> and&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mover><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>&#729;</mo></mover></math> and&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>HCl</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>6</mn></msub></math> and&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>HCl</mi></math>"],"answer":2,"solution":"<blockquote><p>In summer season, chlorine atoms&nbsp;forming chlorine sinks, preventing much ozone depletion, whereas In winter, special type of clouds called polar stratospheric clouds are formed over Antarctica.</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mover><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>&#8226;</mo></mover><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">l</mi><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">g</mi></mfenced><mo>+</mo><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>4</mn></msub><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">g</mi></mfenced><mo>&#8594;</mo><mover><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>&#8226;</mo></mover><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">g</mi></mfenced><mo>+</mo><mi>HCl</mi><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">g</mi></mfenced></math></p></blockquote>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (26 Jul Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":30433,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Hydrocarbons","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/kCOwKMoSABzqDwx5P_XsrE2ryukc0x9YMz97p4tvtE4.original.fullsize.png\"/><br/>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/YhM2_5tQp8l5mLSMbTAIRXaWWK_w1QFGYHkrjxolLKw.original.fullsize.png\"/><br/>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/rqW6nhwiaKj2TPbrsMpYKHWmk2dgAdGwK0gF_sYhCFE.original.fullsize.png\"/><br/>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/l-bfq7tizla_wiQnFB0r7jS6DBz5aIX4HgefQWKyh58.original.fullsize.png\"/><br/>"],"answer":2,"solution":"Stability order of carbocation\n\n\n<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/Fkj0IGogs8bt-LknpwVxOr7PLQc54kwPw5At2h3fOqg.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2025 (29 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":30595,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Hydrocarbons","question":"","options":["<math><mi>A</mi><mo>=</mo><mi> </mi></math> Benzyl alcohol, <math><mi>B</mi><mo>=</mo></math> Benzyl isocyanide","<math><mi>A</mi><mo>=</mo></math> Benzyl chloride, <math><mi>B</mi><mo>=</mo></math> Benzyl isocyanide","<math><mi>A</mi><mo>=</mo></math> Benzyl alcohol, <math><mi>B</mi><mo>=</mo></math> Benzyl cyanide","<math><mi>A</mi><mo>=</mo></math> Benzyl chloride, <math><mi>B</mi><mo>=</mo></math> Benzyl cyanide"],"answer":1,"solution":"<p><img height=\"71\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/89295506-a05d-47ae-9009-49950561ca15-image.png\" width=\"567\" /><br /><br />The final product is an isocyanide as the <math><mi>A</mi><mi>g</mi><mi>C</mi><mi>N</mi></math> bond has covalent nature, due to which <math><mi>C</mi></math> is unavailable for bond. Hence, N bonds with the benzylic carbon leading to formation of isocyanide.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2019 (09 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":30524,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Hydrocarbons","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>III</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>II</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>IV</mi></math>"],"answer":3,"solution":"<p>Only in&nbsp;<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/0dabeb1a-fc69-4272-a42a-af522ecbe520-image.png\" style=\"width: 149px; height: 107px;\" />&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi><mo>-</mo></msup></math>&nbsp;can be substituted by <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi>OH</mi><mo>-</mo></msup></math>, <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi><mo>-</mo></msup></math>&nbsp;combine with <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi>Ag</mi><mo>+</mo></msup></math>&nbsp;to form a yellow precipitate&nbsp;of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>AgI</mi></math>. While</p><p>in <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>II</mi></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>III</mi></math> substitution reaction is not possible due to partial double bond character.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (26 Aug Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":30615,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Hydrocarbons","question":"","options":["Acetylene","Ethene","2 - Butyne","2 - Butene"],"answer":2,"solution":"The 1, 1, 1 - trichloroethane&nbsp;form ​&nbsp;2-butyne&nbsp;when reacted with silver powder.<br /><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><msub><mi>CCl</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>+</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>6</mn><mi>Ag</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#8594;</mo><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>&#8801;</mo><msub><mi>CCH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>+</mo><mn>6</mn><mi>AgCl</mi></math>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2014 (06 Apr)","image":null},{"id":30451,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Hydrocarbons","question":"","options":["\\(\\mathrm{H}_2 \\mathrm{O}, \\mathrm{H}^{+}\\)and \\(\\mathrm{KMnO}_4\\)","\\(\\mathrm{O}_3, \\mathrm{Zn} / \\mathrm{H}_2 \\mathrm{O}\\) and \\(\\mathrm{NaOH}_{(\\text {alc) }} / \\mathrm{I}_2\\)","\\(\\mathrm{O}_3, \\mathrm{Zn} / \\mathrm{H}_2 \\mathrm{O}\\) and \\(\\mathrm{KMnO}_4\\)","\\(\\mathrm{H}_2 \\mathrm{O}, \\mathrm{H}^{+}\\)and \\(\\mathrm{NaOH}_{(\\mathrm{alc})} / \\mathrm{I}_2\\)"],"answer":1,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/nkBLIW6MBikANwzX2grKoRSR54hhLWad1sIIntg9GtQ.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (04 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":30449,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Hydrocarbons","question":"","options":["Statement I is correct but Statement II is incorrect","Statement I is incorrect but Statement II is correct","Both Statement I and Statement II are correct","Both Statement I and Statement II are incorrect"],"answer":0,"solution":"In nitration of benzene concentrated $\\mathrm{H}_2 \\mathrm{SO}_4$ and $\\mathrm{HNO}_3$ is used as reagent which generates electrophile $\\mathrm{N}_2$ in following steps:\n<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/trZlbEBbqm5ay2m4fDwBGirAkzibpJd-0An86hW93aU.original.fullsize.png\"><br />Lewis acids can promote the formation of electrophiles not Lewis base","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (05 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":30428,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Hydrocarbons","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"Organic $\\rightarrow \\mathrm{CO}_2$<br />Compound<br />Applying POAC on ' C '<br />(mole) of ' C ' in compound $=\\mathrm{n}_{\\mathrm{CO}_2} \\times 1$<br />So mass of ' C ' in compound<br />$=\\frac{1.46}{44} \\times 12$<br />So, $\\%$ of ' C ' in compound $=\\frac{1.46}{44} \\times \\frac{12}{0.5} \\times 100$<br />$=79.63$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2025 (3 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":30516,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Hydrocarbons","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn></math> identical mesomers","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn></math> enantiomers","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn></math> enantiomers and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn></math> mesomers","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn></math> racemic and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn></math> enantiomers"],"answer":0,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/7f62a3a6-67e0-46f9-b5e3-6e9b0c245225-image.png\" style=\"width: 490px; height: 170px;\" />","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (01 Sep Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":30436,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Hydrocarbons","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/_r1veNYHwix2gTBGlFAX29NHznq8jpQ49qoCCwb8wg4.original.fullsize.png\"/><br/>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/Z02nY94T-Y3MKlTtDURobvV2XQGkTywFW0TO4DzqcZ8.original.fullsize.png\"/><br/>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/PeC3xaxnkmNrWu5RcG-GsL5RHXVt0putin2Xzi91gRg.original.fullsize.png\"/><br/>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/k_FvmQX-GHCI-Joo17zAljY6NdX9M4aHDWT1d-CVruY.original.fullsize.png\"/><br/>"],"answer":2,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/N2duQphllagxYB-_4gr9j71gnOqleoKbnVGWPRlR8YQ.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2025 (28 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":30403,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Hydrocarbons","question":"","options":["Hept-2-ene","Hept-1,3,5-triene","Heptane","Hept-2,4,6-triene"],"answer":2,"solution":"Compound (X) undergoes isomerization on heating with anhydrous $AlCl_3$ and HCl gas to give branched-chain alkanes. The formation of $2,4$-dimethylpentane (a $7$-carbon branched alkane) indicates that (X) is a $7$-carbon straight-chain alkane.<br><br>Aromatization of n-heptane at high temperature and pressure in the presence of oxides of V, Mo, or Cr supported over alumina gives toluene.<br><br>Cyclisation of n-heptane under similar conditions initially yields methylcyclohexane, which can further undergo dehydrogenation to form toluene.<br><br>Since all these reactions are characteristic of n-heptane, compound (X) is heptane.<br><br>Answer: Heptane","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2026 (02 April Shift 2)","image":null}]